      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Proponents of these theories, such as J.P. Rushton and Richard Lynn, point to studies on cranial size, brain structure, and genetic variation among different racial groups to argue that there are biological differences that contribute to IQ disparities. They claim that East Asians, for example, have a more efficient brain structure and a larger brain-to-body mass ratio, which allows for better cognitive processing. Additionally, they point to genetic studies that suggest that certain genetic variants, such as the APOE gene, are more common in East Asians and are associated with higher IQ. They also argue that the genetic differences between racial groups are due to evolutionary pressures, such as climate and diet, which have favored the development of certain cognitive abilities in certain populations.",
